  "prompt": "When is surge pricing on Uber generally in effect in Detroit and how high does it go?",
  "response": "Surge pricing on Uber in Detroit, as in other cities, typically comes into effect during times of high demand and limited supply of drivers. This can occur during rush hours, major events, holidays, inclement weather, or any situation where many people need rides simultaneously. The exact times and conditions can vary, but peak surge pricing often happens:\n\n1. Weekday mornings (approximately 7-9 AM) when people are commuting to work.\n2. Weekday evenings (approximately 4-7 PM) when people are commuting home.\n3. Weekend nights (approximately 9 PM-2 AM) when people are going out or returning home.\n4. During events such as concerts, sports games, festivals, or large conventions.\n5. During severe weather conditions, like snowstorms or heavy rain, which increase demand for rides.\n\nThe surge multiplier, which determines how much higher the fare is compared to normal rates, can vary widely. During extreme demand periods, surge pricing can sometimes make fares 2-3 times higher, and in rare cases, it can go higher than that. However, specific multiplier rates and caps can change based on Uber's policies and the dynamics in Detroit.\n\nFor a precise understanding of surge pricing at any given time, it's best to check the Uber app, as it displays current rates and any surge pricing in effect at the moment of booking.",
